{"abstract":[{"text":"Functions that would be instance methods if tuples could be extended.","type":"text"}],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"type":"heading","text":"","anchor":"","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Some of the functions in this package should be considered “instance methods”. If tuples were a named type, we could extend them with real methods that incorporate dot syntax."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For example, to add 1 to a tuple of integers, we’d "},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"like","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" to be able to write:"}]},{"code":["let tuple = (1, 2, 3)","tuple.map { $0 + 1 }"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"…but the best we can do is:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["map(tuple)() { $0 + 1 }"]},{"level":4,"text":"Recommended Mental Model for “Tuple Instance Methods”: Unsugared Instance Methods","type":"heading","anchor":"Recommended-Mental-Model-for-Tuple-Instance-Methods-Unsugared-Instance-Methods"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Say that we want to use "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/swift\/collection\/map(_:)","type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" on an "},{"code":"Int Array","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":". Because "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Array"},{"text":" is a named type, Swift provides that functionality using this syntax:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["[1, 2, 3].map { $0 + 1 }"]},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"But this is sugar for what’s really going on. Swift’s ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"instance"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" methods are actually ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"type"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" methods, which accept an instance as their argument, and return a closure. We typically think of this closure as the instance method itself.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To illustrate this, here’s an "},{"code":"Array","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" extension:"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["extension Array {","  func method() { }","}"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"You’d normally call that using this syntax:","type":"text"}]},{"code":["let instance = [1, 2, 3]","instance.method()"],"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"But it’s also available as a "},{"code":"static","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" method, on "},{"code":"Array","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", and can alternatively be called like this:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","code":["Array.method(instance)()"],"syntax":"swift"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"map"},{"text":" from the standard library can similarly be called like so:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","code":["Array.map(instance)() { $0 + 1 }"],"type":"codeListing"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"That’s how the package authors think about the functions cataloged below."}]},{"type":"aside","style":"note","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"It’s unfortunately not possible to remove the “","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"()"},{"type":"text","text":"” before trailing closures without access to "},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"real","type":"text"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":" instance methods. The limitation has been logged as a bug for years.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}],"name":"Note"}],"kind":"content"}],"variants":[{"paths":["\/documentation\/tuple-\/instance-methods"],"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}]}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/xn--tupl-epa\/documentation\/Tupl-"]]},"metadata":{"roleHe